Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy or BSE is commonly known as "mad cow
disease".  The disease was first diagnosed in 1986, and exhibits
symptoms to those of scrapie, a sheep disease that has been seen in
England since the 1700s. The incurable disease eats holes in the
brains of its victims, and in its later stages causes the animals to
act skittish or stagger drunkenly. As of February this year the
British government had ordered the destruction of 10,000 cattle, and
had spent the equivalent of 6.1 million dollars to compensate the
owners of the destroyed animals.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA042290-0104"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

Ten thousand cattle have been killed in Britain in an attempt to limit
the spread of the "mad cow disease". Experts suspect that the disease
is spread through cattle feed that contains sheep by-products that are
used as protein supplement. In June 1988 the government banned the use
of sheep offal in cattle feed, but new cases of the disease are still
being reported. The government contends that the disease poses no
threat to humans.  The United States and several other countries have
banned the importation of British beef.</SUM>

<SUM
