SUMMARIZER="C"> 

Researchers at the National Institutes of Health in Bethesda, Maryland
are studying the human version of spongiform encephalopathy known as
Creutzfeldt-Jakob, or CJD.  Scientists had agreed that the spongiform
disease found in sheep and that found in cattle probably posed no
threat to humans. Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease has been rare, but they
have been confounded by the relatively large outbreak of CJD in an
area of Slovakia where most people raise and care for sheep. The
British are intensely interested in anything that links humans to the
animal form of the spongiform disease.</SUM>

<SUM
