It was reported this week that a dairy farmer, Mr. Peter Warhurst,
died last year of Creutzfeldt Jakob disease. Mr. Warhurst's herd had a
case of "mad cow disease", or BSE, in 1989. Both BSE and CJD are
caused by mysterious particles of infectious protein called prions The
British government maintains that beef can be eaten safely, and that
there is no causal link between BSE and CJD. The death of the dairy
farmer and the continued rise in the number of cases of BSE has fueled
the growing public anxiety surrounding bovine encephalopathy.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT933-8272"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

New cases of mad cow disease", or BSE, are still being reported at a
rate of about 1000 per week. Last month a second dairy farmer,
Mr. Duncan Templeman, succumbed to Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, a human
brain ailment similar to BSE. The new cases and the deaths of two
dairy farmers have prompted a new wave of public criticism of the
government officials who stoutly maintain that there is no evidence
that BSE contributed to the deaths. The government still insists that
scrapie-contaminated feed is the cause of the reported cases of
BSE.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS3-41815"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

The London zoo's small herd of kudu has been hit by a strain of the
"mad cow disease".  Five of the eight kudu born at the zoo since 1987
have contracted the disease. Only one of the five could have eaten
feed that contained sheep protein. Such contaminated food has been
identified as the source of the disease in cattle. The disease has
also been found in domestic cats, and in the larger cheetah and
puma. Scientists at the zoo feel the outbreak in the kudu herd shows
some species are more vulnerable than others.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FBIS4-35908"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

Germany has asked the European community to sanction Germany's ban on
British beef imports, claiming that the request is justified because
of the potentially grave health risks.  As of last week 121,898 cattle
in Britain had been diagnosed with "mad cow disease".  Over 8,000
cattle have died of the disease even though they were born after the
government had banned the processed feed suspected to be the source of
the disease.  Even with those discouraging numbers, and evidence the
disease has spread to other species, Britain maintains it is no threat
to humans, and that the German request is frivolous.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT941-1547"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

Seven universities and research institutes in Germany have been
commissioned to examine possible connections between the origins of
"mad cow disease" and two human diseases. Those diseases,
Creutzfeldt-Jakob and Gerstmann Straussare are rarely seen, but the
German government is trying to convince the European Union that
Germany should be allowed to ban the import of British beef. More than
100,000 cattle in Britain have died after contracting the "mad cow
disease". Fifty cases have been reported in Switzerland, and two in
Germany, one of which affected a cow imported from Britain.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d05"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT941-575"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="C"> 

Tomorrow the Health Ministers of the European Union will consider
Germany's request to ban British beef exports because of the fear of
Bovine Spongiform Encephalopathy, or BSE, commonly known as "mad cow
disease". The United Kingdom feels that the ban on export of live
cattle and of the offspring of BSE-affected cows that has been in
effect since 1990 is working well.  That ban, plus other restrictions,
in addition to the lack of firm scientific evidence of a link between
BSE and Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that affects humans make the British
confident that The European Union will deny Germany's request.</SUM>
